== Use Case 2: The "I'm Broke Until Friday" Week

_Situation:_ It's Tuesday. Payday isn't until Friday. You have \$11 in your checking account and a fridge full of scraps.

_Drain Salad strategy:_

+ _Take inventory:_ What scraps do you have? Wilted greens? Stale bread? Onion ends? Parmesan rinds? List everything.

+ _Make stock or soup:_ Combine all your scraps in a pot with water, salt, and a spoonful of miso. Simmer for 30 minutes. You now have 6 cups of soup that cost \$0.

+ _Make bread-based dishes:_ If you have stale bread, make panzanella or bread pudding. Bread + scraps + eggs/cheese = a meal that feels substantial.

+ _Stretch with grains:_ If you have dry rice, pasta, or beans in the pantry, cook them and use scraps as the "topping." A small amount of scraps + a lot of grain = full stomach.

#hero-image("../manuscript/images/chapter-11/074_broke-week-fridge.png", caption: [A "broke week" fridge with only scraps and pantry staples - before and after transformation into a meal])

_Why this works:_ Scraps are free. You've already paid for them when you bought the original vegetables. Using them is pure profit.

_Personal note:_ This was me, November 2021 to March 2022. Four months of this. Every meal was scraps + pantry staples. I didn't starve. I didn't eat badly. I learned more about cooking in those four months than I did in two years of school.

